from Ipsos import *

To ensure a better visualization and understanding of this notebook, Ipsos.py file is implemented.

It contains 5 classes :

[!] Data -> It contains methods that allow us to annotate data without doing it manually ! 
[!] Viz  -> It allows us to visualize and explore our data.
[!] ML   -> It allows us to construct the whole pipeline of ML (i.e. from preprocessing to fitting model)
[!] DL   -> It allows us to construct the whole pipeline of DL (i.e. preprocessing, building vocab ... to fitting model)
[!] RNN  -> It's sub-class of nn.Module. It's used for building DL model

/!\ A detailed explanation of each class is provided in the next sections :)

)

In [8]:
# I'll use this function to compute accuracy 
# in next step 
def compute_accuracy(model, data_loader, device):

    with torch.no_grad():

        correct_pred, num_examples = 0, 0

        for i, (features, targets) in enumerate(data_loader):

            features = features.to(device)
            targets = targets.float().to(device)

            logits = model(features)
            _, predicted_labels = torch.max(logits, 1)

            num_examples += targets.size(0)
            correct_pred += (predicted_labels == targets).sum()
    return correct_pred.float()/num_examples * 100
In [9]:
start_time = time.time()

train_acc = []
val_acc = []
train_loss = []
val_loss = []

for epoch in range(NUM_EPOCHS):
    model.train()
    for batch_idx, batch_data in enumerate(train_loader):
        
        text = batch_data.TEXT_COLUMN_NAME.to(DEVICE)
        labels = batch_data.LABEL_COLUMN_NAME.to(DEVICE)

        ### FORWARD AND BACK PROP
        logits = model(text)
        loss = F.cross_entropy(logits, labels)
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        
        loss.backward()
        
        ### UPDATE MODEL PARAMETERS
        optimizer.step()
        
        ### LOGGING
        if not batch_idx % 50:
            print (f'Epoch: {epoch+1:03d}/{NUM_EPOCHS:03d} | '
                   f'Batch {batch_idx:03d}/{len(train_loader):03d} | '
                   f'Loss: {loss:.4f}')


    with torch.set_grad_enabled(False):
        print(f'training accuracy: '
              f'{compute_accuracy(model, train_loader, DEVICE):.2f}%'
              f'\nvalid accuracy: '
              f'{compute_accuracy(model, test_loader, DEVICE):.2f}%')
        train_acc.append(compute_accuracy(model, train_loader, DEVICE))
        val_acc.append(compute_accuracy(model, val_loader, DEVICE))
        
    print(f'Time elapsed: {(time.time() - start_time)/60:.2f} min')
    
print(f'Total Training Time: {(time.time() - start_time)/60:.2f} min')
print(f'Test accuracy: {compute_accuracy(model, test_loader, DEVICE):.2f}%')

# Saving prediction in csv file 
def predict_and_save(data, model, model_name, whole_X):
    
    if model_name == 'SVM' :
        path = 'OUTPUT/result_svm.csv'

    elif model_name == 'BNB' :
        path = 'OUTPUT/result_bnb.csv'

    elif model_name == 'LR' :
        path = 'OUTPUT/result_lr.csv'
        
    print(f'[!] Predicting sentiments... ')
    whole_Y = model.predict(whole_X)
    
    print(f'[!] Saving Predictions...')
    data['Sentiment'] = whole_Y
    
    data.to_csv(path, index = False)
    print(f'[!] Done ! Results was saved to {path} :)')

4. WHY ? 🔼¶

A. These models 🔼¶

[!] We are dealing with a problem of sentiment's classification (positive or negative).

[!] To the best of my knowledge, i'd rather test SVM first because :

[!] It can be used in non-regularly distributed ( i.e. Data that has unknown distribution) -> after applying TF-IDF to 
our data, we don't have any idea about the distribution that's why  ! 

[!] The outliers are less influence on the model -> In our case, sometimes some comments seem for TextBlob like 
positive (it identified it like positive) but it's sarcastic. For example : "Lmao everyone hates Dasani it's so funny. Give me whatever. As long as its room temperature & not thick im straight"

[!] For Logistic Regression, I choose it because :

[!] It makes no assumptions about the distributions of classes in feature space. (Same as SVM)
[!] We can interpret the model after building it.

[!] For Bernoulli Naive Bayes, in order to confirm my hypothesis (during the interview) being aware that it is not the best option to consider (same as Gaussian Naive Bayes):

[!] In fact, their problem is that they assume that the features are supposed independent !
[!] In our case features are strongly dependent since we are working with sentences

[!] For LSTM, I implemented, but I usually use it when I have big texts as input to avoid the problem of Long Term dependencies.

B. These metrics 🔼¶

[!] As stated previously, our data is balanced

[!] Accuracy is good representative metric of the model performance.

[!] But, during all projects I prefer also to use F1-score, It's more reliable than other metrics in most cases.

5. Conclusion & Perspectives 🔼¶

[!] SVM gives us best result, but we can improve it :

[!] By fine-tunning its hyperparameters using Gridsearch

[!] For LSTM, we can improve it by :

[!] Testing other architectures
[!] Regularization
[!] Performing dropout to avoid Overfitting

/!\ If there is some misclassed sentiment, it can be due to the annotation ! not to models
